summary:
A Kuwaiti tanker full of oil caught fire off Dubai after sustaining damage Tuesday, one day after President Trump's threats against Iran. The owner warns of a potential oil spill. This incident affects global shipping lanes amid the U.S.-Israeli campaign against Iran. 

Spain denied U.S. warplanes use of its airspace and Andalusia military bases for Iran operations, impacting U.S. logistics in Europe. Saudi Arabia and UAE urged Trump to extend the month-long U.S.-led strikes on Iran, stating they have not sufficiently weakened Tehran. Asian nations including Thailand increased purchases of Russian crude as the Iran war reduces 20% of global oil supply through the Strait of Hormuz. China's manufacturing PMI rose to 50.4 in March from 49.0, per the National Bureau of Statistics, ending contraction. 

Rwanda-backed rebels fired gunshots inside Goma, overrunning troops in the safe-haven city and displacing over one million, according to residents and the U.N. Israel opened a military zone allowing displaced Palestinians to cross into northern Gaza after a hostage release. NATO deployed its first coordinated units following a new Baltic Sea cable cut suspected as sabotage. Myanmar junta leader Min Aung Hlaing won a lower house vice-president vote Tuesday, with two other military-aligned candidates also elected; a presidential vote follows this week. Eight people died in a crowd crush at Sheetla temple in Nalanda, Bihar, India, during prayers; the chief secretary is probing security lapses and families receive 600,000 rupees each. A U.S. Fourth Circuit panel paused a lower court ruling, allowing Trump's executive orders to halt federal diversity programs."}
